SATIRE VI.

In this satire Horace attempts to show that real greatness is quite independent of external circumstances3 and that true no- bility consists in personal worth, and not in the distinctions of birth and family. He mentions his own case as a proof thar Maecenas selected his friends for their personal qualities ; since he had no advantages of family to recommend him, And he pays a grateful tribute to the memory of his father for having trained him in the path of virtue, and instilled those principles into his mind which· seem to have laid the foundation of his happiness.
